ğŸ“Œ Concepts: Dynamic Programming, Optimization
ğŸ“Œ Difficulty: Medium
ğŸ“Œ Very common in OA + interviews

ğŸ” Problem Statement

You are given an integer array nums where:

nums[i] = amount of money in the i-th house

Houses are in a straight line

âš ï¸ Constraint:
You cannot rob two adjacent houses (police alert system).

ğŸ‘‰ Find the maximum amount of money you can rob.

ğŸ§ª Examples
Example 1
Input: nums = [1,2,3,1]
Output: 4


Explanation:
Rob house 1 (1) + house 3 (3) â†’ total = 4

Example 2
Input: nums = [2,7,9,3,1]
Output: 12


Explanation:
Rob houses 2 (2) + 4 (9) + 6 (1) â†’ total = 12

ğŸ§  Core Idea (IMPORTANT FOR INTERVIEWS)

At each house, you have two choices:

1ï¸âƒ£ Rob this house

Then you must skip previous house
2ï¸âƒ£ Skip this house

Take best till previous house

So:

dp[i] = max(
    dp[i-1],           // skip current
    nums[i] + dp[i-2]  // rob current
)

ğŸ› ï¸ Algorithm (Optimized DP)

We donâ€™t need full DP array, only last two values.

â±ï¸ Complexity
Type	Value
Time	O(n)
Space	O(1)
ğŸ’» Java Code (Interview-Perfect)
class Solution {
    public int rob(int[] nums) {

        int prev2 = 0; // dp[i-2]
        int prev1 = 0; // dp[i-1]

        for (int num : nums) {

            int curr = Math.max(prev1, prev2 + num);

            prev2 = prev1;
            prev1 = curr;
        }

        return prev1;
    }
}

ğŸ§¾ Line-by-Line Explanation
int prev2 = 0;
int prev1 = 0;


â¡ï¸ Stores results for:

prev2 â†’ house i-2

prev1 â†’ house i-1

int curr = Math.max(prev1, prev2 + num);


â¡ï¸ Decide:

Skip current house

OR rob it and add value from i-2

prev2 = prev1;
prev1 = curr;


â¡ï¸ Shift values for next iteration

ğŸ§ª Dry Run Example
Input:
nums = [2,7,9,3,1]

House	Money	Max Till Now
0	2	2
1	7	7
2	9	11
3	3	11
4	1	12

â¡ï¸ Output = 12

